   <title>Examples of Hyperspaces</title>
	  <caption>Hyperspaces - Examples</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The set of solutions of the equation</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>{\color{red} 2}x + {\color{blue} 3}y = 0</latex>
			      </math.display>
			      <para>
            <para.body>forms the line through the origin of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> which is <subordinate>
                  <hot>perpendicular</hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>
                        <caption>Why is this line perpendicular to c?</caption>
                     </info.caption>
					
					                <para>
                        <para.body>Because <math>
                              <latex>{\color{red} 2}x+{\color{blue} 3}y = \DotPr{ ({\color{red} 2},{\color{blue} 3}) }{ (x,y) }</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </info>
               </subordinate> to the vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{c} = ({\color{red} 2},{\color{blue} 3})</latex>
               </math>. This line is an example of a hyperspace in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <para align="center">
            <para.body>
				           <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="ims/HyperSpace2D_Exmpl.gif"/>
               </media>
			         </para.body>
         </para>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Notice that a linear equation of the form</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>{\color{red} 2}x + {\color{blue} 3}y = 0</latex>
			      </math.display>
			      <para>
            <para.body>always reveals a normal vector to the hyperspace of its solutions, namely the vector <math>
                  <latex>({\color{red} 2},{\color{blue} 3})</latex>
               </math> of its coefficients.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The set of solutions of the equation</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>{\color{red} 2}x + {\color{red} 9}y {\color{red} - 3}z = 0</latex>
			      </math.display>
			      <para>
            <para.body>forms the plane through the origin of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math> which is <subordinate>
                  <hot>perpendicular</hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>
                        <caption>Why is this plane perpendicular to n?</caption>
                     </info.caption>
					
					                <para>
                        <para.body>A point <math>
                              <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                           </math> belongs to the given plane exactly when its position vector <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x} = (x,y,z)</latex>
                           </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{n} = ({\color{red} 2},{\color{red} 9},{\color{red} -3})</latex>
                           </math>. This happens exactly when</para.body>
                     </para>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>0 = \DotPr{ \Vect{n} }{ \Vect{x} } =  \DotPr{ ({\color{red} 2},{\color{red} 9},{\color{red} -3}) }{ (x,y,z) } = {\color{red} 2}x + {\color{red} 9}y {\color{red} -3}z</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </info>
               </subordinate> to the vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{n} = ({\color{red} 2},{\color{red} 9},{\color{red} -3})</latex>
               </math>. This plane is an example of a hyperspace in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
